DESIGN DECISIONS (executor, O9.1 - full list also in RESULT.md)
D1. Workspace layout: QROKY_WORKSPACE_DIR default ./qroky (same variable name
    and default as 071's bootstrap.sh for continuity). Inside it, TOP LEVEL
    (not nested under another qroky/): framework/ (vendored, git checkout
    pinned to a release tag once one exists, else pinned SHA - same known
    limitation as 071), install-state.json, install.log, decisions/ (self-
    update mini-atom records), .qroky/telegram.token (mode 600, the ONLY
    place the bot token is ever written).
D2. State file: hand-written flat-key JSON (no jq dependency - POSIX+curl+git
    only, H1). Every key name is globally unique across the whole document
    (step_* / answer_* prefixes) so a single grep -oE "\"KEY\": *\"...\"" per
    field is unambiguous regardless of nesting - same "no YAML library,
    template regular enough" reasoning push.sh already uses for status.yaml.
    Whole file is rewritten fresh on every commit from the process's own
    shell variables (no associative arrays - bash 3.2 compat, same
    constraint 071/RESULT.md flagged for macOS stock bash).
D3. Interactive prompts: real `read -r` (unlike 071's zero-question
    bootstrap.sh) because THIS atom's mandate is explicitly an interview -
    every read call is tagged inline with a comment `# IV-POINT:<n>:<name>`
    so the harness can grep-count the question inventory against the closed
    list of 7 (H2 check: "question inventory equals the closed list").
D4. Test stubs: PATH-shadowing (fake claude / curl / launchctl binaries, and
    a local offline git repo standing in for the framework remote) is the
    primary stub mechanism, following 071's proven, already-reviewed
    pattern, so install.sh needs zero test-mode branches for those three.
    ONE explicit QROKY_TEST_STUBS=1 in-script hook exists, clearly marked,
    for the "subscription/login" heuristic only (skips a soft credential-
    file probe that would otherwise print a spurious NOTICE in every sandbox
    run since the sandbox HOME never has real Claude Code credentials) -
    matches INPUT's explicit instruction ("e.g., QROKY_TEST_STUBS=1") while
    keeping every other path production-identical.
D5. Self-update mechanics live inside install.sh itself as flags
    (--check-update, --show-update-details, --apply-update) rather than a
    separate always-running daemon script, because the deliverable list
    (INPUT section 2) does not name a separate heartbeat file - install.sh
    generates the user-facing heartbeat runner + launchd plist into the
    workspace at Step 7 (heartbeat step), adapted from
    runtime/claude/heartbeat/* with the END USER's own paths substituted (no
    reference to this repo's paths), and that generated runner calls
    `install.sh --check-update` daily. This keeps H1 "single entry point"
    literally true - one script the user ever has to know about - while
    still shipping a real, working self-update channel.
D6. Kill-mid-install test hook: QROKY_TEST_DELAY_STEP / QROKY_TEST_DELAY_SECONDS
    env vars, read only if set (absent by default = zero effect on
    production runs), inserted before ONE step's state commit so the harness
    has a deterministic window to SIGKILL the process mid-step and prove
    resumability against real, already-committed prior-step state.

HARNESS CHECKLIST (knowledge/reference/harness-checklist.md, 9 points) - walked
before any sandbox scenario touches its stub data, per role's Harness
Discipline (INFO-025).
1. State-file and resumability: install-state.json (D2 above), lives in the
   user's workspace, survives process death (plain file, not in-memory).
   Rerun resumes at the first non-done step; answered steps never re-asked.
2. Idempotency: every step function is check->do; a rerun on a healthy
   workspace reports each step's check as already satisfied and changes
   nothing (health-check no-op) - proven in dry-run scenario "healthy rerun".
3. Auto-attempt limit: 2 per step (network retry / lock wait / permission
   hint), 3rd failure of the same step always escalates to a concrete human
   instruction - implemented as a shared run_with_ladder() wrapper, proven in
   the "broken dependency" scenario.
4. Secret redaction: bot token written ONLY to .qroky/telegram.token (mode
   600); install-state.json stores telegram_token_stored=yes/no (boolean),
   never the token value; install.log never echoes the raw token (masked
   before any log line). Negative grep proven in its own dry-run scenario.
5. Self-contained log + relay: install.log is human-readable, readable
   without session context (each line: timestamp, step, verb, outcome);
   critical events (step failed 3x, secret-adjacent action, self-update
   applied) also land in the one-line delegation-style summary this run.log
   captures per scenario, and self-update additionally relays into the
   user's own decisions/ record (mini-atom, H11).
6. Budget line: install.sh has no token/API cost of its own to track (it is
   the user's local shell process, not an LLM call) - the budget line that
   applies is THIS build's own (see BUDGET CHECKPOINTs + RESULT.md cost
   block), logged here rather than invented for the artifact itself. Logged
   as an explicit SKIP with this justification, not a silent omission.
7. Dependencies: git (framework vendoring + self-update fetch) - official,
   already a hard H1 dependency, no degradation path other than the existing
   fail() message naming the install command; curl (Telegram getMe) -
   official Bot API, opt-in step, degrades to "skip Telegram, continue" if
   unreachable (skippable per H2); claude CLI - official, hard H1 dependency
   per the parent framework's own binding; launchctl (heartbeat) - macOS-only
   official tool, degradation path is documented (Windows/Linux: "no
   launchctl" NOTICE + manual one-command instruction, same shape as 071's
   crontab fallback).
8. Verify before first live run: this atom's own products are blind-verified
   (ATOM-101-VERIFY) before ANY real founder touches install.sh; inside this
   build, every dry-run scenario is exercised against the sandbox before
   RESULT.md is filed - no scenario is claimed passing without a captured
   transcript.
9. Happy-path question, three "what if"s: (a) killed mid-install -> rerun
   completes from the first non-done step (scenario: kill-mid-install); (b)
   run twice -> second run is a no-op health-check (scenario: healthy
   rerun / double-run idempotency diff); (c) no network -> concrete human
   instruction naming the exact blocked operation (scenario: broken
   dependency). All three are scripted scenarios below, not asserted by
   argument.

